<h2 id="building-a-gaming-pc-for-beginners">Building a Gaming PC for Beginners</h2>

<p>A lot of beginners want to <a href="/budget-pcs/">build a gaming PC</a>, but they donâ€™t really know where to start.</p>

<p>Letâ€™s talk a little bit about choosing the components for your PC build.</p>

<h3 id="choosing-your-processor-and-graphics-card">Choosing Your Processor and Graphics Card</h3>

<p>A lot of first-time builders make the mistake of wasting too much money on a fast CPU and a ton of RAM, but they donâ€™t spend enough on the graphics card.</p>

<p>Thatâ€™s a fatal mistake. Hereâ€™s why:</p>

<p>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphics_processing_unit" target="_blank">GPU</a> (Graphics Processing Unit) is responsible for 3D rendering, which is the primary gaming related task.</p>

<p><img class="lazyload img-middle" alt="Ryzen processor cover image" data-src="/img/600/ryzen-cover.jpg" /></p>

<p>If youâ€™re building a gaming PC for $600, youâ€™re going to want to spend as much as you can on your GPU.</p>

<p>Still, that doesnâ€™t mean you should spend too much on it.</p>

<p>I know that sounds contradictory, so let me explain:</p>

<p>Some people â€“ rather than overspending on the processor â€“ overspend on the GPU, and they buy a processor thatâ€™s too old and slow.</p>

<p>This will lead to something known as a CPU bottleneck, which will kill the performance potential of your gaming PC and result in a pretty bad experience overall, especially if the games youâ€™re playing require a decent amount of processing power.</p>

<p>The CPU isnâ€™t the primary component in a gaming PC, but it still has to process a lot of informationâ€¦ thatâ€™s a given.</p>

<p>If your GPU is too fast, your processor wonâ€™t be able to keep up.</p>

<p>Imagine trying to pair an Intel Pentium CPU with a GTX 1080 Ti.</p>

<p>Obviously, the 1080 Ti has way more processing power than the Pentium.</p>

<p>In this scenario, the Pentium CPU would be at 100% usage, causing frame drops, stutters, and ultimately limiting the power of the graphics card.</p>

<p>On the other hand, what if you bought an Intel i7 8700K (a top of the line CPU) and paired it with a GTX 750 Ti (an old, slow GPU)?</p>

<p>Youâ€™d have another bottleneck on your hands, but this time the graphics card would be too slow to keep up with the graphics card.</p>

<div class="tip">
	<h4 class="info-box-header">Tip<i class="box-icon-spacing fas fa-check"></i></h4>

<p>Hereâ€™s the key to building a 600 dollar gaming PC on a budget:</p>

<p>Choose the best graphics card you can, and then buy a CPU that is good enough to keep up. </p>

<p>Itâ€™s all about buying a CPU/GPU combo that compliments one another. </p>

</div>

<p>Luckily, we were able to select a powerful graphics card and a powerful processor, so weâ€™re all set.</p>

<h3 id="choosing-a-motherboard">Choosing a Motherboard</h3>

<p>When youâ€™re building a $600 gaming PC, you donâ€™t need to go all out on your motherboard.</p>

<p>Some expensive motherboards come with a bunch of bells and whistles, such as M.2 slots, a ton of SATA connectors, fancy LEDs, and more.</p>

<p>All of those features are nice, especially if youâ€™ve got a lot of money to spend â€“ but not on a $600 budget.</p>

<p>When youâ€™re choosing a gaming motherboard for a budget PC, you should stick to the basics.</p>

<p><strong>Here are the things to focus on:</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>Socket type</li>
  <li>Chipset</li>
  <li>RAM support</li>
  <li>Storage options</li>
  <li>Form factor</li>
  <li>BIOS</li>
  <li>Fan Headers</li>
  <li>Crossfire/SLI support</li>
</ul>

<p>Letâ€™s go over each of those points in a bit more detail:</p>

<p>Socket type and form factor are pretty straightforward.</p>

<p>First of all, you should know the size (form factor) of your motherboard so you can make sure itâ€™s compatible with your case. In addition, larger motherboards tend to have more features.</p>

<p><img class="lazyload img-middle" alt="Gigabyte motherboard cover image" data-src="/img/mobo/mobo-diagram.jpg" /></p>

<p>You should also definitely know your motherboardâ€™s socket type, as this will determine which CPUs your motherboard is compatible with.</p>

<p>In the unfortunate event you buy a motherboard with the wrong socket type, youâ€™re going to be out of luck.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s important to make sure you have the right chipset. Low-end chipsets donâ€™t support overclocking.</p>

<p>Since weâ€™re using a Ryzen CPU in this build, you should buy a motherboard that supports overclocking, as Ryzen CPUs benefit tremendously from overclocking.</p>

<p><a href="https://linustechtips.com/main/topic/955775-difference-between-b350-and-b450/" target="_blank">B350/B450 chipsets</a> are, in general, the low-end chipsets that still support overclocking.</p>

<p>With all of that being said, choose a motherboard that:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Is Cost-effective</li>
  <li>Has Crossfire/SLI support if you want it (not feasible on a $600 budget)</li>
  <li>Has enough SATA ports</li>
  <li>Has USB 3.0</li>
  <li>Is compatible with your CPU</li>
  <li>Supports overclocking</li>
  <li>Has enough fan headers for your build</li>
  <li>Sufficient RAM slots with adequate speed support</li>
</ul>

<p>You should also check the motherboardâ€™s BIOS reviews â€“ some are easier to use than others, and you donâ€™t want to be stuck with a complicated BIOS as a beginner.</p>

<h3 id="choosing-ram">Choosing RAM</h3>

<p>A lot of inexperienced PC builders make the mistake of going overboard when it comes to RAM.</p>

<p>In reality, you donâ€™t need all that much, at least when it comes to gaming. 16GB of fast RAM is recommended for optimal performance, although itâ€™s far from necessary.</p>

<p>Ryzen performance benefits significantly from having plenty of high speed RAM to work with. Still, if youâ€™d rather allocate the money elsewhere â€“ say, for extra storage â€“ 8GB of RAM will still do in 2020.</p>

<p><img class="lazyload img-left" alt="RAM left side image" data-src="/img/600/vengeance-left.jpg" /></p>

<p>Besides, you can always upgrade in the future.</p>

<p>Conversely, if youâ€™re the kind of person who likes to multitask a lot, youâ€™re going to want the extra RAM.</p>

<p>Google Chrome â€“ the most popular browser on the web â€“ uses a lot of RAM, and itâ€™s hard to game with satisfactory frame rates while you have a few Chrome tabs open.</p>

<p>RAM is also great for other workstation tasks such as streaming, recording, editing, and rendering.</p>

<p><strong>Whatâ€™s the bottom line here?</strong></p>

<p>You can run 16GB of RAM in your build for optimal performance at a higher cost, or you can save some money and get by with 8GB.</p>

<p>Think of the extra 8GB as a power up.</p>

