<h2 id="should-you-buy-an-ssd">Should You Buy an SSD?</h2>

<p>In short, yes, yes you should.</p>

<p>Solid State Drives (SSDs) significantly improve your PCâ€™s overall performance.</p>

<p>Although more expensive than traditional storage solutions, theyâ€™re well worth the money.</p>

<p>You can pick up a 240GB SSD for around $60. Thatâ€™s a perfect amount of storage for your Windows OS, drivers, and some games.</p>

<p><img class="lazyload img-left" alt="ssd vs hdd" data-src="/img/600/ssd-vs-hdd.jpg" /></p>

<p>Seriously, spend the extra money. If youâ€™ve ever felt like you have to let your computer â€˜warm upâ€™ for a while after you turn it on, itâ€™s probably because your Windows is loaded on a mechanical hard drive.</p>

<p>Mechanical drives are cheap and great for mass storage, but thatâ€™s about it.</p>

<p>If you install your Windows on an SSD, your PC will cold boot (that is, powering on from a completely turned off state) to being fully functional and ready to go in less than 30 seconds. Really, Iâ€™m not kidding.</p>

<p>Moreover, youâ€™ll find your applications loading far quicker, not to mention your games.</p>

<p>If you have the extra money to spend, buy an SSD.</p>

<p>A 1TB mechanical drive will cost you around $50, whereas a 240GB SSD will run you around $60. However, itâ€™s well worth the investment.</p>

<p><img class="lazyload img-middle" alt="m2 drive" data-src="/img/600/m2-drive.jpg" /></p>

<p>In another life (probably two years ago) I only had a 1TB mass storage mechanical drive.</p>

<p>That was such a big mistakeâ€¦</p>

<p>I only had to pay $45 for a WD Caviar Blue drive, which I thought was a steal â€“ and, in all honesty, it is a steal.</p>

<p>So, if itâ€™s such a great deal, why am I complaining?</p>

<p>When youâ€™re booting up your PC, launching a game and trying to load in, or launching a bunch of applications at once, a mechanical drive simply wonâ€™t do.</p>

<p>When I finally decided to upgrade, I moved my operating system and drivers to an SSD, and my computer booted in less than 30 seconds, and it was ready for action.</p>

<p>The story is the same with my games â€“ I was always one of the first, if not the first, to load in.</p>

<p>No more waiting around, dealing with games crashing, or being the last to load. For more information about how SSDs work, click <a href="https://www.makeuseof.com/tag/solidstate-drives-work-makeuseof-explains/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>

<p>Nevertheless, itâ€™s always a good idea to have a mass storage mechanical drive to serve as a cheap storage solution.</p>

<p>When you need to store files that donâ€™t need to be loaded quickly â€“ such as music, movies, some applications, etc. â€“ a mechanical drive will do just fine.</p>

